### Step 2: Initialize Your Local Repository

Open your terminal (PowerShell) **in your `knowmap_project/` folder**. Make sure your `(venv)` is active.

Run these three commands one by one:

1.  **Initialize Git:**
    ```bash
    git init
    ```
2.  **Add all files** (this will automatically skip the files in your `.gitignore`):
    ```bash
    git add .
    ```
3.  **Create your first "save"** (a commit):
    ```bash
    git commit -m "Initial commit of Knowmap project"
    ```

### Step 3: Create a New Repository on GitHub

1.  Go to [GitHub.com](https://github.com) and log in.
2.  Click the **`+`** icon in the top-right corner and select **"New repository"**.
3.  Give your repository a name (e.g., `knowmap-project`).
4.  **IMPORTANT:** Do **NOT** check any boxes to add a `README`, `license`, or `.gitignore`. Your project already has these.
5.  Click **"Create repository"**.

### Step 4: Push Your Code to GitHub

After creating the repository, GitHub will show you a page titled "…or push an existing repository from the command line".

Copy those three commands and run them in your terminal. They will look like this (but with your username and repository name):

1.  **Link your local repo to the one on GitHub:**
    ```bash
    git remote add origin https://github.com/your-username/knowmap-project.git
    ```
2.  **(Good practice) Rename your main branch to `main`:**
    ```bash
    git branch -M main
    ```
3.  **Push (upload) your code:**
    ```bash
    git push -u origin main

